<br>
.evn. <p></p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub25.ezboard.com/uevnhnssn.showPublicProfile?language=EN>evn hnssn</A> at: 6/6/01 9:00:34 am<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#aaaaaa><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub25.ezboard.com/usofianime.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Sofianime</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Karbonite</span><br> <font color=#336699>(6/6/01 10:45:17 am)</font><br>    <BR><img src=http://www16.brinkster.com/sofianime/lilicon3b.jpg height=100 width=100></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Person-Object Interaction</span><hr size=1> Draw the chair first on a piece of paper. Then put a piece of tracing paper on top of the drawing of the chair and draw your character on it.  You can create the pose as a stick figure first, until you are happy with the pose and then flesh out the character.  After that you can put the two drawings together and voila! It will look good..That's how we draw things in animation. We layer everything.<br>
Hope that helps ya!<br>
Oh, and always keep it simple <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START ;) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/wink.gif ALT=";)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
Sofi! <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :D --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/happy.gif ALT=":D"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#CCCCCC><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub25.ezboard.com/usketchboarder.showPublicProfile?language=EN>sketchboarder</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC=http://www.ezboard.com/ezgfx/gicons/white_ball.gif BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Pre-Karbonite</span><br> <font color=#336699>(6/7/01 10:43:02 am)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Hmm...</span><hr size=1> Well, if you know anything about perspective drawing, I would recommend this procedure:<br>
<br>
First- Set the horizon line, as was suggested in an earlier reply, then depending where you want your character/object in the scene create a 1pt or 2 pt perspective so you can keep things in line and so that you have good reference to where the feet and shadow should be.<br>
<br>
Second- Draw a stick figure casually sitting on the chair, (keep in mind, you should point mark the hip and shoulders.) If you want, get a friend to sit in the chair while you do this... Or go to polykarbon.com and check out the Head-body ratio of what a character needs in order to be in proportion. (HINT: Make sure that you put emotion into the stick figure first! EX: If he/she is bending over draw the arch etc.)<br>
<br>
Third- Create a light source so that you know where your highlight/shadow spots are going to be. Once you have all of this, you can add Detail.<br>
<br>
Well I hope that this helps, if you have anymore questions feel free to E-mail me at Sketchboarder@hotmail.com or instant message me on AIM-  Pip Stick 69<br>
